THE TERM DOCK WORKER OBSERVED TWO EMPTY TOTES THAT HAD RESIDUE ON THE TOPS. THEY CALLED THE 24HR RESPONSE NUMBER.  THE TERM REQUESTED AN MSDS AND ANY INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO CLEAN UP.  THEY ADVISED THE TERMINAL WEAR RUBBER GLOVES AND GOGGLE TO WIPE DOWN THE TOTES AND CONTAIERIZE THE RAGS.  THE TOTE BUNGS WILL BE TIGHTENED AND WILL BE FORWARDED ON, THERE IS NO MORE LEAK.

WHILE UNLOADING A DOCK WORKER NOTICED A WET CTN.  HE NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR AND CONTACTED THE ER NUMBER.  ONE JUG WAS LEAKING FROM BEING CRUSHED.  THEY WERE ADVISED THAT THE TERMINAL NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL AND CONTAINERIZE IT FOR DISPOSAL.  THE SHIPPER WOULD LIKE THE DAMAGED CONTAINER DISPOSED OF ALSO.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, DOCKMAN DISCOVERED DAMAGED AND LEAKING BAGS. RECOOPED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED DOT APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER AND HELD FOR SHIPPER DISPOSITION.  SPILLED MATERIAL SWEPT UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  REMAINDER OF FREIGHT FORWARDED.
WHILE UNLOADING, DISCOVERED DAMAGED AND LEAKING DRUM.  RECOUPED INTO PLASTIC LINED PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  SPILLAGE ABSORBED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED.

A CARTON WAS DAMAGED WHILE LOADING.  CARTON PLACED IN PLASTIC LINED PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  SPILLAGE ABSORBED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

THE TERMINAL WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER AND RIPPED A BAG ON THE BOTTOM OF A STACK ON A SKID WITH ANOTHER PALLET.  ONE BAG WAS RIPPED OPEN AND ABOUT 1 CUP OF POWDER SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE TERM CONTACTED THE 24HR RESPONSE NUMBER.  THEY ADVISED THE TERMINAL TO WEAR GLOVES, GOGGLES, BOOTIES, A DUST MASK, AND A TYVEK SUIT WHILE CLEANING THIS UP.  THEY SHOULD OVERPACK THE BAG AND PLACE THE SPILLED PRODUCT INTO A SACK AND THEN IN THE OVERPACK.  THEY SHOULD PLACE ALL CLEAN UP AND PPE INTO A SEPARATE DRUM AND HOLD ALL FOR DISPOSITION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DURING A YARD SWITCH, SHOVE MOVEMENT, RAILCARS INADVERTENTLY SHOVED OVER A CROSS-OVER SWITCH TO THE MAIN TRACKS STRIKING TWO STANDING COAL TRAINS ON THE MAIN TRACKS.  THE TWO LEAD CARS IN THE SHOVE DERAILED, INCLUDING ACFX 87191 WHICH SUSTAINED A PUNCTURE HOLE ON THE A-END TANK HEAD CORNER AT APPROX. THE 8 O'CLOCK POSITION.  IT APPEARED THAT THE TANK HEAD WAS PUNCTURED BY THE TWISTED-OFF DRAWBAR ASSEMBLY OF THE LEAD RAILCAR DERAILING IN THE SHOVE MOVEMENT.  INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED THAT THE RADIO CONTROLLED CROSS-OVER SWITCH WAS NOT LOCKED EFFECTIVELY COUPLED WITH THE FAILURE OF THE CREW TO CONTROL THE SHOVE MOVEMENT.  THE FLOW OF ESCAPING COMMODITY WAS REDUCED BY PLUGGING HOLE & REMAINING COMMODITY WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR.  SPILLAGE WAS VACUUMED UP & IMPACTED/CONTAMINATED SOIL REMOVED. THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF US HIGHWAY 77 OVERPASS ABOVE THE DERAILMENT SITE WAS CLOSED FOR APPROX. 8 HOURS.

column168: ON OCTOBER 13, 2004 AT 0355 HOURS TANK CAR ACFX 94588 WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TILFORD YARD.  AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT, THE ACFX94588 WAS ROLLED ONTO IT'S SIDE AT APPROXIMATELY THE SEVEN O'CLOCK POSITION.  CSX MANAGEMENT OBSERVED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM UNDERNEATH THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER (BREADBOX).  CSX IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THEIR TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE ACCORDING TO REGULATORY REQUIREMENTS.  SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND FOUND THE TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE LIQUID LINE VALVE AND THE MOUNTING PLATE.  SWS WAS UNABLE TO TIGHTEN DOWN THE FOUR BOLT/NUT CONNECTION ENOUGH TO SECURE THE RELEASE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT APPLIED FOAM TO THE CAR WHICH ENABLED THE RERAILING CONTRACTORS TO SAFELY UPRIGHT THE CONTAINER.  ONCE UPRIGHTED THE LEAK SUBSIDED.  APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO THE BALLAST MEDIA.  THE PRODUCT IN THE DAMAGED TANK CAR IS SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSFERRED THEN THE CONTAINER WILL BE CLEANED AND PURGED.  AFTER THE CAR IS CLEANED AND PURGED, THE LIQUID LINE WILL BE REMOVED ALLOWING FOR FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE GASKET AND MOUNTING SURFACE.

I CALLED 3-E FOR A RESPONSE TEAM.  THE RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1300 HRS.  THEY (ENVIROSOLV) OVERPACKED THE LEAKING DRUM AND CLEANED THE AREA THAT HAD BEEN CONTAMINATED, CLEANED THE TRAILER TO STOP ANY FURTHER LEAKING AND MOVED THE TRAILER TO TULSA, OK APPROX 30 MILES TO INVORSOLV: THE LOAD WAS THEN TRANSLOADED TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  OKLAHOMA DEQ WAS INFORMED AND A REPORT TO THE NRC WAS MADE TO (DEWESSE) #737226.

ACCORDING TO REPORTS, THE LEAK WAS NOTICED AT 10:30 PM AS THE CAR WAS SITTING IN THE BNSF RAIL YARD.  FIRST RESPONDERS FROM THE BNSF HAZMAT TEAM RESPONDED TO THE LEAK AND WERE ABLE TO PLUG THE HOLE.  APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF COOPER CHLORIDE MATERIAL SPILLED BEFORE THE HAZMAT TEAM COULD STOP THE LEAK.  THE LEAK OCCURRED CLOSE TO THE UNDERSIDE OF THE RAILCAR ABOUT ONE FIFTH OF THE WAY UP THE CAR FROM BOTTOM.  THE SIZE OF THE LEAK WAS APPROXIMATELY TWO INCHES IN DIAMETER AND THE HOLE WENT THROUGH THE SHELL OF THE RAILCAR AND THE INNER LINER.  THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE LEAK HAD NOT BEEN DETERMINED, BUT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE CORROSION SINCE THERE IS LITTLE EVIDENCE OF RUST AROUND THE HOLE OF THE RAILCAR.  AT THIS POINT, OUR BEST GUESS IS THAT SOME SORT OF PROJECTILE MIGHT HAVE POSSIBLY STRUCK THE RAILCAR.

ON OCTOBER 6, 2004 TWO SUPERIOR EMPLOYEES WERE FILLING A BULK LOAD OF TOLUENE FOR A PHARMACEUTICAL COMPANY.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS WERE WARM WITH LOW RELATIVE HUMIDITY AND VERY LITTLE WIND.  NO SIGNIFICANT RAIN FALL HAD OCCURRED WITHIN THE PREVIOUS 30 DAYS.  THE PRODUCT WAS BEING FILTERED THROUGH A TWO INCH STAINLESS STEEL, ONE MICRON FILTER CANISTER VIA CHEMICAL HOSE.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE FOLLOWING AN ESTABLISHED STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURE FOR TOP LOADING AND FILTERING WITH A MICRON FILTER.  THE TANKER, FILTER AND LOADING RACK WERE ALL APPROPRIATELY BONDED AND GROUNDED.  THE PRIMARY LOADING EMPLOYEE WAS VISUALLY OBSERVING THE LOADING OF THE TOLUENE IN THE NEAR VICINITY OF THE FILLING OPERATION.  JUST AS THE TANKER WAS NEARING 100% OF THE SCHEDULED DELIVERY AMOUNT A FLASH FIRE OCCURRED IN THE VAPORS ABOVE THE MANY WAY.  THE LOADER WAS LIFTED OFF OF THE TANKER LOADING PLATFORM BY THE INITIAL SHOCK WAVE AND THROWN TO THE GROUND.  THE EMPLOYEE RECEIVED SECOND AND THIRD DEGREE BURNS PRIMARILY TO THE HANDS, FOREARMS AND BACK.  THE LOADING ASSISTANT WAS IN THE ADJACENT AREA CONVERSING WITH THE LOADER AT THE TIME OF THE FLASH FIRE.  BOTH EMPLOYEES INDICATE THAT NO GAUGING, SAMPLING, HOSE HANDLING OR OTHER OPERATIONAL ACTIVITY WAS TAKING PLACE AT THE TIME OF THE FLASH FIRE.  THE LOADING ASSISTANT RECEIVED "SUNBURN" LIKE BURNS TO THE FACE AND LIPS AND FIRST TO SECOND DEGREE BURNS ON THE LEFT FOREARM.  BOTH EMPLOYEES AT THE TIME OF THE FLASH FIRE WERE FOLLOWING SUPERIOR'S PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT POLICY FOR THE TASKS THEY WERE COMPLETING.  TWO UV/IR DETECTORS WITHIN THE AUTOMATIC FIRE DETECTION SYSTEM ALARMED AND INITIATED AN AUTOMATIC DELUGE FOAM-WATER FIRE SUPPRESSION SYSTEM.  THE FIRE ALARM PANEL MADE IMMEDIATE AUTOMATIC NOTIFICATION TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND RELEASED THE SECURITY GATE FOR FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONSE.  THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED IN THREE MINUTES AND FOURTEEN SECONDS.  THE FIRE WAS COMPLETELY EXTINGUISHED IN ONE MINUTE AND SEVENTEEN SECONDS FROM THE INITIAL DELIVERY OF THE FOAM WATER SOLUTION. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND AMBULANCE SERVICE ARRIVED ON SCENE WITHIN FIVE MINUTES OF NOTIFICATION TO TREAT AND TRANSPORT THE INJURED EMPLOYEES.  NO RESPONSE ACTION WAS REQUIRED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM.  THE FIRE WAS COMPLETELY SUPPRESSED BY THE TIME OF THEIR ARRIVAL AND NO LIQUID RELEASE OF TOLUENE HAD OCCURRED.  A PRIMARY AND SECONDARY SPILL CONTAINMENT SYSTEM CONTAINED THE FOAM AND FIRE WATER RUNOFF, FOR SUBSEQUENT DISCHARGE APPROVAL.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT PLANT AND WAITED UNTIL TOLD THEY WERE READY FOR THE DELIVERY.  DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO THE STORAGE TANK AREA.  HE NOTICED THAT THE DELIVERY WAS TO BE MADE TO A DIFFERENT TANK THAN PREVIOUS DELIVERIES, AS THE PIPING HAD BEEN MODIFIED.  HE CONNECTED HIS HOSES AND BEGAN DELIVERY.  FIVE MINUTES INTO DELIVERY, A PLANT EMPLOYEE CAME OUT, AND SIGNED OFF ON THE DELIVERY PAPERWORK, AND MARKED DOWN THE LIQUID LEVEL IN THE STORAGE TANK.  APPROXIMATELY AN HOUR LATER, THE SAME EMPLOYEE CAME BACK AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER THAT THE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING AND TO SHUT DOWN THE DELIVERY.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN HIS PUMP AND COMPRESSOR AND CLOSED THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE TRAILER.  PLANT EMPLOYEE CLOSED THE FACILITY'S VALVE. PLANT'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND CONTAINED THE VAPOR RELEASE THROUGH THE USE OF WATER.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE FULL TANK TO AN ADJACENT EMPTY ONE TO ALLOW THE DRIVER TO COMPLETE HIS DELIVERY.  APPROXIMATELY 600 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED ON-SITE.

column25: G & S MOTOR EQUIPMENT CO INC
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: A SHIPMENT OF USED TRANSFORMERS CONTAINING PCB OIL WAS TRANSPORTED BY SJ TRANSPORTATION FROM G & S MOTOR EQUIPMENT, KEARNY, NJ TO PELL CITY, AL, WITH AN ADDITIONAL PICKUP AT TCI, HUDSON, NY.  WHILE ENROUTE TO HUDSON, NY, ONE TRANSFORMER FELL FORWARD IN THE TRAILER, STRIKING AND PUNCTURING THE FRONT WALL OF THE TRAILER WHEN THE DRIVER BRAKED FOR A TRAFFIC LIGHT.  THE IMPACT WITH THE TRAILER WALL CAUSED AN INSULATOR ON THE TRANSFORMER TO BREAK OFF AND PCB-CONTAMINATED OIL TO ESCAPE.  THE OIL LEAKED BETWEEN THE OUTSIDE AND INSIDE WALLS OF THE TRAILER, BYPASSING THE TRAILER CONTAINMENT SYSTEM.  THE OIL THEN ESCAPED THE TRAILER, LEAKING ONTO THE TRACTOR AND GROUND.  UPON REALIZATION OF THE LEAK, THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE AND BEGAN EMERGENCY CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT WHO THEN CONTACTED THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES (NYDEC & USEPA REGION II).  AN EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND BY THE TRANSPORTER.  REMEDIAL ACTION WAS TAKEN TO RETURN THE SITE TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR UNDER THE AUSPICIOUS OF THE NYDEC.  ALL SITE SAMPLES WERE SENT TO THE ACCREDITED LABORATORY FOR TESTING.  ALL MATERIALS RESULTING FROM THE REMEDIATION OF THE SITE AND EQUIPMENT WAS PROPERLY PACKAGED BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR.  THE MATERIALS WERE THEN TRANSPORTED BY SJ TRANSPORTATION TO PROPERLY LICENSED TSD'S UNDER THE FOLLOWING MANIFESTS: 00004; NYB2689182; NYB2689155; NYB2689164.  AN ANALYSIS OF THE INCIDENT PERFORMED BY THE TRANSPORTER REVEALED A DEFICIENCY IN THE LOADING AND BRACING PROCEDURES. ACTION WAS TAKEN BY THE TRANSPORTER TO DEVELOP AND IMPLEMENT A REVISED LOADING AND BRACING PROCEDURE TO PRECLUDE FURTHER INCIDENTS.

WE HAVE ALSO DEVELOPED TRAINING MATERIAL AND WILL HOLD TAILGATE MEETINGS IN REGARD TO THE HANDLING OF TOTES.

column168: DURING THE OFFLOAD OPERATIONS THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THE INNER CAPS ON SIX OF THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE OFF OR VERY LOOSE.  NO POSITIVE CLOSURE.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET INDICATES THIS MATERIAL HAD A FLASH POINT OF 134 F, WHICH MAKES IT A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, CLASS 3.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE LOCAL FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column42: HYDROFLUORIC ACID, WITH NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT STRENGTH
column168: THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND IN THE FAR RIGHT HAND LANE EN-ROUTE TO TORONTO, IL LOADED WITH 38,860 LBS OF HYDROFLUORIC ACID. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER HE NOTICED WHAT APPEARED TO BE A MIST BEING DISCHARGED OFF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT COMING FROM AN AREA AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER APPROXIMATELY 2/3 OF THE WAY UP THE TRAILER.  ONCE THE PRESSURE HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER THE PRODUCT WAS NO LONGER BEING DISCHARGED FROM THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER.  THE PRODUCT BUILDS APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 LBS OF PRESSURE WHILE IN-TRANSIT.  CTL NOTIFIED THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE ABOUT THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT AND THEY RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO CONTROL TRAFFIC.  AT THIS TIME THERE WAS NO MEASURABLE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED.  CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES WAS CONTACTED BY CTL TO MANAGE THE TRANSFER AND ANY CLEAN UP THAT WOULD BE REQUIRED.  CURA DISPATCHED BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL TO THE SCENE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR LATER THE TRAILER DEVELOPED A STEADY LEAK APPROXIMATELY THE SIZE OF A PENCIL.  THIS IS WHEN THE ILLINOIS STATE POLICE SHUT THE INTERSTATE DOWN IN BOTH DIRECTION FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 HOURS.  CTL SENT ANOTHER DRIVER AND TRAILER TO THE SCENE AND IT ARRIVED WITHIN 30 MINUTES AFTER THE INITIAL LEAK HAD BEEN DETECTED. SOLVAY FLUORIDES WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY SENT OUT A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THERE ALORTON, IL FACILITY WITH A DIAPHRAGM PUMP AND ADDICTION HOSES AND FLANGES TO AFFECT THE TRANSFER.  ONCE ON SCENE THE TRAILER WAS PUMPED DOWN BELOW THE AREA THAT HAD BREACH AND THE LEAK HAD BEEN STOPPED.  THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT WAS ALSO TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  LIME WAS PLACED IN THE AREA OF THE RELEASED PRODUCT TO NEUTRALIZE THE PRODUCT.  BODINE ENVIRONMENTAL SECURED THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 AM.  THE TRAILER IS A CUSTOMER OWN TRAILER AND SLOVAY FLUORIDES HAS TAKEN FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE CLEAN UP AND HAS ENGAGED A SPECIALIST TO DETERMINE THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE LINER FAILURE.  ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE LAST INSPECTION PERFORMED.  CTL HAS NOT RECEIVED TO DATE SOLVAY FINDINGS ON THE LINER FAILURE.  CTL DISTRIBUTION REPORT TO THE NCR WHEN THE INITIAL RELEASE HAPPENED (NCR FILE # 737705) AND WHEN THE SECOND RELEASE OCCURRED A CALL WAS PLACED TO REPORT THE SECOND RELEASE (NCR FILE #737724) THIS CALL WAS PLACED IN SOLVAY FLUORIDES.
LOADED TRAILER AND DROVE TO GUARD SHACK AND WAS TOLD THE BLEEDER VALVE WAS LEAKING. DRAINED THE PRODUCT FROM BETWEEN INTERNAL & EXTERNAL AND CHANGED GASKET AN THE BLEEDER VALVE.

DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING AND WAS BLOWING LINES.  THE AIR LINE WAS MISSING A GASKET AND PRODUCT SPRAYED OUT GETTING SOME ON DRIVERS CHEEK & HANDS WHEN HE TOOK HIS GLOVES OFF.  DRIVER PUT A NEUTRALIZING ON IT AND WASHED.  OK NO TIME LOST.

THE FILL LINE ATTACHES TO A FLANGE AT THE TOP OF THE TANK WHERE THE PRODUCT ENTERS.  DURING UNLOAD THE FLANGE BEGAN TO LEAK.  RINSED DOWN WITH WATER BY PLANT PERSONNEL.
ONE OF THE CUSTOMERS INTERIOR PIPES BURST AT A STRAIGHT JOINT CONNECTING TWO STRAIGHT PIPES.  THEIR WAS A PVC PIPE.  HAD TO SHUT DOWN AND REPAIR. WASHED DRUM INTO SYSTEM WITH WATER.

TANK OVERFLOW.  ABOUT 10 MINUTES OFTER THE DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING AND HAD CLOSED HIS VALVES.  CUSTOMER CAME OUT & SAID THERE WAS AN OVERFLOW. CUSTOMER THEN FOUND SITE GAUGE AND HAD TO CLEAN IT OFF TO READ IT.  USUALLY CUSTOMER ORDERS 40000 POUNDS AND THIS TIME THEY RECEIVED 45000 POUNDS.  ALL PRODUCT WENT INTO A CONTAINED AREA.

VAPOR FROM THE CAR WAS RELEASED BETWEEN BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP AND THE VALVE.  THE VALVE CAP WAS FOUND TO BE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT UPON FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE CAR.  AFTER THE CAR WAS RERAILED, THE VALVE CAP WAS TIGHTENED, AND THE VALVE HANDLE WAS CLOSED, STOPPING THE LEAK.

column168: GATX 200073, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUIFIED, WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE THE DOME LID OPEN IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SAGINAW, MI.  WHEN THE CAR INSPECTOR CLIMBED THE CAR TO CLOSE THE LID, HE REPORTED HEARING A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE VALVES INSIDE THE DOME. THE GENERAL CAR FOREMAN AT THE YARD RESPONDED AND INSPECTED THE VALVES IN THE DOME.  HE REPORTED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LEAKING VAPORS AROUND THE VALVE PLUG.  THE VAPOR VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE OPEN SLIGHTLY.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED TIGHTLY AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  THE GENERAL FOREMAN REPORTED THE VALVE PLUG APPEARED TO BE TIGHT.  THE DOME LID WAS SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER, MARATHON ASHLAND WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND ADVISED OF THE CONDITION THAT CAUSED THE VAPOR RELEASE.  THEY INDICATED THAT THEY WOULD INVESTIGATE THE MATTER.

LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WERE SUMMONED.  RAILROAD PERSONNEL MOUNTED THE CAR AND DETECTED AN ODOR INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL MOUNTED THE CAR AND FOUND THE SAMPLE LINE PLUG REMOVED AND A PIPE ADAPTER ATTACHED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL TIGHTENED THE SAMPLE VALVE AND NO ADDITIONAL ODOR WAS OBSERVED.  THE PIPE ADAPTER WAS REMOVED AND A REPLACEMENT PLUG WAS INSERTED INTO THE SAMPLE LINE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT AFTER LAW ENFORCEMENT PERSONNEL COMPLETED THEIR INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON SUNDAY, OCTOBER 17, 2004 LAS RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED A BAGGAGE TUB WITH CONTAMINATED RAGS AND JET FUEL ON FLIGHT 2431 FROM SEA. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON THURSDAY, OCTOBER 21, 2004, 4:15 PM, OIL TRANSPORT'S DRIVER EXITED I95 AT EXIT 98 TO DELIVER LOW SULFUR DIESEL TO THE DOSWELL ALL AMERICAN TRAVEL PLAZA.  AS THE DRIVER GOT OFF THE EXIT RAMP, HE MOVED INTO THE LEFT LANE TO MAKE A LEFT TURN INTO THE TRUCKSTOP.  AS HE SLOWED DOWN TO 20 MPH, THE LIGHT TURNED GREEN.  WHILE MAKING THE TURN, HE STRAIGHTENED HIS TRUCK AND TRAILER AND FELT THE TRUCK ROLL OVER.  THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND SKIDDED 50-75 FEET BEFORE STOPPING.  DIESEL FUEL STARTED LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  BULKHEADS WERE CRUSHED.  THERE WAS A CRACK IN THE FORWARD BULKHEAD COMPARTMENT AND TWO CRACKS AT THE MIDSHIP BULKHEAD OF THE TRAILER. EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE CONTACTED IMMEDIATELY.  VA. DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (DEQ), DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY SERVICES (DES), HANOVER FIRE, POLICE & SHERIFF PERSONNEL, INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES, ENGINEERING CONSULTING SERVICES, MARSHALL MILLER & ASSOCIATES ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE AND ENGINEERING, #1 TOWING AND REPAIR, OIL TRANSPORT RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT WERE ALL ON SITE WITH OTHERS TO BE NAMED ON THE SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT.  EVERETTE CLAIM SERVICE, REPRESENTING CANAL INSURANCE AND OIL TRANSPORT, WAS ALSO ON SITE WITHIN 45 MINUTES.  MIKE WHITE, CANAL INSURANCE EPA MANAGER, VISITED THE SITE.  OIL TRANSPORT WAS INVOLVED IN CONTACTING EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AND COORDINATING SUPPORT.  OIL TRANSPORT IMMEDIATELY COORDINATED AND SATISFIED ALL EMERGENCY PERSONNEL REQUESTS. OIL TRANSPORT WAS INSTRUMENTAL IN RESPONDING TO ALL EMERGENCY PERSONNEL REQUIREMENTS TO TRANSPORT OIL WATER MIX AWAY FROM THE SITE WITH COMPANY TANKERS OVER NUMEROUS DAYS.  ALL 8,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE TRUCKSTOP PAVEMENT AND IN A STORM DRAIN OVER 5 HOURS.  THE HANOVER FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURED THE SPILL WITH SAND AND TARPS.  INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE (IMS) ALSO CONTAINED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND BOONS AT THE SITE IN A HOLDING POND WATERWAY BEHIND THE TRUCKSTOP.  IMS AND MARSHALL MILLER & ASSOCIATES SECURED & REMEDIATED THE SITE ACCORDING TO GUIDELINES SET BY THE COMMONWEALTH OF VIRGINIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES.  THE SITE IS UNDER REMEDIATION ACCORDING TO THESE GUIDELINES.  A SUPPLEMENTAL REPORT WILL BE FILED AFTER THE SITE REMEDIATION IS COMPLETED AND SIGNED OFF BY DEQ AND DES.

column62: Abrasion; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VEHICLE IN QUESTION WAS LOADED WITH 73,740LBS, NET OF MOLTEN SULFUR AND WAS WITHIN 5 MILES OF DESTINATION.  THE TRUCK HAD JUST TURNED OFF OF WY HWY 376 A RIGHT TURN, AND WAS PROCEEDING DOWN HILL ON MARCHANT ST.  THE UNIT WOULD HAVE MADE A RIGHT TURN ON A YIELD BUT AS IT SLOWED FOR THE TURN THE NOSE OF THE SEMI TRAILOR CAME UP AND OFF OF THE 5TH WHEEL.  THE SMI TRAILOR AND PUP PASSED THE TRACTOR ON THE LEFT, WENT DOWN THE HILL, CROSSED OVER US HWY 430 AND INTO A FENCED PARKING AREA.  THE SEMI CAME DOWN ON THE LOADING LEGS AND AS IT ENTERED THE PARKING LOT IT FLIPPED OVER AND SLID ON THE ASPHALT AND SCRAPPED OFF THE LID OF THE TANK.  THE PUP TRAILER DID NOT TURN OVER.  AS THE DOME COVER HAD COME OFF THE LIQUID CONTENT OF THE TANK SPILLED OUT AND THE 290F HEAT OF THE SULFUR CAUSED THE TIRES ON THE PUP TO CATCH FIRE.  THE LIQUID RAN UNDER THE FENCE AND INTO A LOW AREA CONTAINING STANDING WATER FROM RAIN.  THE LIQUID SULFUR IMMEDIATELY COOLED AND BECAME HARD.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY AND USED FOAM TO PUT OUT THE FIRE. THE HIGHWAY PATROL INVESTIGATED AND FOUND THAT THE KINGPIN OF THE TRAILER HAD NOT BEEN DOWN INTO THE JAWS OF THE 5TH WHEEL AND INSTEAD HAD JUST RIDDEN ON TOP OF THE JAWS UNTIL IT CAME UNHOOKED AND THE TRAILERS HAD SEPARATED FROM THE TRACTOR.  SINCE THE ACCIDENT, SAFETY MEETINGS HAVE BEEN HELD AND THE DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO LOOK CLOSELY AT THE 5TH WHEEL AFTER HITCHING.  MAKE SURE THAT THE JAWS ARE CLOSED AROUND THE KINGPIN. ALSO LOOK FOR LIGHT BETWEEN THE 5TH WHEEL PLATE AND THE KINGPIN PLATE ON THE TRAILER IF THERE IS NOT A GOOD LATCH, THE LIGHT SHOULD BE EVIDENT THERE.  AND MAKE SURE THE INDICATOR BOLT IS IN, THE LATCH HANDLE IS IN, AND THE JAWS ARE CLOSED.  PULL AGAINST THE KINGPIN TO MAKE SURE IT DOES NOT POP UP.

column168: AT OUR MAKAKILO FACILITY ASPHALT PLANT OUR TANKER TRUCK WAS UNLOADING HOT LIQUID ASPHALT IN OUR ASPHALT PLANTS HOLDING TANK #2 AND THE MECHANICAL TANK OVERFLOW SYSTEM FAILED TO INDICATE THAT THE HOLDING TANK WAS NEARING ITS CAPACITY.  TANK OVERFLOWED OUT OF THE OVERFLOW PIPE, WHICH IS LOCATED IN THE BACK OF THE TANK IN A HARD TO SEE LOCATION.  THE UNLOADING OPERATOR THAN NOTICED LIQUID ASPHALT COMING OUT FROM UNDER THE HOLDING TANK AND THAN REALIZED THE TANK HAD OVERFLOWED.  WHERE-BY THE OPERATOR STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE SPILL WAS CONFINED TO UNDER AND AROUND THE HOLDING TANK.  AS SOON THE ASPHALT COMES INTO CONTACT WITH THE GROUND IT COOLS VERY QUICKLY SO THE MATERIAL DID NOT TRAVEL VERY FAR.  EMPLOYEES AT THE PLANT PLACED SOME MATERIAL BERMS JUST TO MAKE SURE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AROUND THE STORAGE TANK.  AS SOON AS THE LIQUID ASPHALT WAS COOL ENOUGH IT WAS CLEANED UP AND RECYCLED.  WE ARE IN THE PROCESS OF LOOKING INTO A HIGH-TECH ELECTRONIC METHOD OF BEING ABLE TO DETERMINE THE LEVEL OF LIQUID ASPHALT IN THE HOLDING TANK TO PREVENT OVERFLOW FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: OPERATOR CONNECTED TO THE "A" SIDE LIQUID VALVE ON RAIL CAR GATX 92739 AND OPENED IT.  SOME AMMONIA LEAKED OUT. column168: DURING STRIPPING OF AN INBOUND SHUTTLE FROM J3, THE UNLOADER FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING AT ITS BOTTOM.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN HIT BY THE CHIME OF ANOTHER DRUM OR BY A FORK.  DOCK PERSONNEL OVERPACKED IT AND PUT IN INTO OS&D. THEY CLEANED UP THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH OIL DRY.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: DURING DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THE DRIVER OBSERVED PAINT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  IT WAS FOUND TO BE COMING FROM THE DISCHARGE PORT OF ONE TOTE.  THE SAFETY CAP WAS MISSING FROM THE PORT.  THE CONSIGNEE PROVIDED MATERIALS AND ASSISTANCE TO CLEAN THE LEAKAGE UP FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THEY ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT AND GAVE THE DRIVER A CLEAR RECEIPT.

DURING RELOAD, ONE PAIL WAS FORKED AT THE BOTTOM.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS LEAKED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  DOCK PERSONNEL USED OIL DRY TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLAGE.  A SHORT TIME AFTER SWEEPING UP THE OIL DRY, ALL OF THE RESIDUE EVAPORATED.  NO ADDITIONAL CLEANING WAS NEEDED.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS HELD IN OS&D.

AFTER UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE/WAREHOUSE'S FACILITY, THE RECEIVER OBSERVED A SMALL QUANTITY OF POWDER ON THEIR DOCK FLOOR.  ONE BAG APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN FORCED UP AGAINST A PALLET AT SOME TIME.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PACKED INTO A BAG.  THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CONSIGNEE/WAREHOUSE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WITH A NOTATION OF ITS CONDITION.  NO CLEAN UP OF THE TRAILER WAS NEEDED.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A NAIL PROTRUDING FROM THE PALLET PUNCTURED THE PAIL.  ABOUT A PINT OF PRODUCT LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR, WITH SOME SPILLING ONTO THE PAVEMENT OUTSIDE THE DOCK DOOR.  HAZMAT GAVE INSTRUCTIONS TO USE OIL DRY ON THE FLOOR AND THE GROUND TO CONTAIN AND ABSORB THE SPILLAGE.  THE PAIL IS TO BE OVERPACKED.  THE OIL DRY IS TO BE SCOOPED UP AND BAGGED.  THE BAG IS TO BE PUT INTO THE OVERPACK WITH THE PAIL.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DURING DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THEY FOUND ONE DRUM LEAKING THROUGH ITS LID.  THERE WAS RESIDUE ON THE SIDE OF THE DRUM BUT NONE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT AND MADE A NOTE OF THE DRUM'S CONDITION.  NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.

AS AN UNLOADER WAS BEGINNING TO STRIP AN INBOUND TRAILER, HE ENCOUNTERED A STRONG ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  HE INVESTIGATED AND FOUND ONE DRUM OF PHENOL LEAKING AND ANOTHER SEVERELY DENTED.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SHIPMENT, PATCHED AND OVERPACKED.  THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  THE DRUMS AND THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PUT INTO OS&D.

DURING DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE, THEY AND THE DRIVER FOUND A QUANTITY OF MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  ONE BAG AT THE BOTTOM OF ITS SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET HAD BEEN FORKED DURING LOADING.  CONSIGNEE'S PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND DRUMMED IT FOR DISPOSAL.  THEY DID NOT ATTEMPT TO REMOVE THE BAG FROM ITS PALLET AT THIS TIME.

TOTE ARRIVED AT BROOK PARK, OH ON A SHUTTLE FROM NEWARK, NJ.  IT HAD A SMALL HOLE IN AN UPPER CORNER RADIUS.  IT APPEARS AS IF SOMETHING HAD BEEN SET ON TOP OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE WHICH THEN DISTORTED.  THE TOTE WAS HELD IN WEST CHESTER, OH.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT OIL DRY ON THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB THE SPILLAGE THEN PACKED IT INTO A DRUM.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage
column168: RESPONDED TO A WET PACKAGE IN THE SORT AISLE AND DISCOVERED IT TO BE A WET HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.  REFERENCE THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET AND PLACED IT IN A SPILL TUB.  MOVED PARCEL TO DAMAGE AREA FOR PROCESSING.  FOUND 5 GALLON CONTAINER OF ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL WITH A LOOSE CAP.  CONTAINER WAS SOILED, SO ALL CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THROUGH DMP. PROPER PAPERWORK WAS COMPLETED.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: RESPONDED TO A FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL WEARING FULL PPE.  THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON IT'S SIDE AND SOAKED THROUGH ON TWO SIDES OF THE CARTON.  I FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR CLEAN UP.  THEN THE PACKAGE WAS MOVED TO THE DAMAGE AREA FOR PROCESSING.  TWO OUT OF THE FOUR GALLONS HAD LOOSE CAPS.  THEY WERE PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.  THE OTHER TWO GALLONS WERE CLEAN AND RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.
RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUID  BROUGHT PACKAGE TO CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING THROUGH DMP.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Corrosion - Exterior; Dropped
column168: I RESPONDED TO A WET BOX IN THE SORT AISLE WEARING PPE AND DISCOVERED A WET HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE.  NOTHING HAD SPILLED OUTSIDE THE BOX.  PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE DAMAGE AREA FOR PROCESSING AFTER CONSULTING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET.  ONCE IN THE DAMAGE AREA, THE ENTIRE CONTENTS WERE NEUTRALIZED USING SODIUM BICARB.  THE PACKAGE WAS THEN PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.  PROPER PAPERWORK THEN COMPLETED.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: I RESPONDED TO A SPILL WITH FULL PPE ON.  UPON DISCOVERY, THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS A FIRE EXTINGUISHER BEING SHIPPED AS A CONCEALED HAZARD SHIPMENT.  FOLLOWED DECISION TREE & RESPONSE SHEET AND TRANSPORTED TO DMP AREA.  DISPOSED OF CONTENTS PER NON-REGULATING LISTING.  RETURN NON-HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TO SHIPPER.

WHEN I NOTICED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL LEAK I FIRST CALLED JEFF TURNER (CWX SAFETY SUPERVISOR) TO THE SCENE.  I THEN TOOK PICTURES OF THE LEAKING PRODUCT AND PLACED IN 25 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  FINALLY I WAS ADVISED TO FILL OUT A CHEMICAL INCIDENT REPORT AND 5800 FORM.  ONE BOX WAS PINNED BETWEEN A PALLET AND THE TRAILER WALL, ARROWS WERE FACING SIDEWAYS CAUSING 4 OZ TO LEAK.  EMPLOYEE WILL BE RETRAINED ON HOW TO PROPERLY LOAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

THE PAIL WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED.  EXAMINATION OF THE PAIL REVEALED THE PAIL HAD A LOOSE CAP/LID AND LEAKED.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE CAP/LID WAS SECURED.  UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT CYLINDER(S) HAD A LOOSE VALVE(S) AND LEAKED. THE VALVE(S) WERE SECURED. THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

UNDAMAGED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED PRODUCT WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED ON THE PROPERTY OF A CUSTOMER OF THE REPORTING CARRIER.  THE CARRIER WAS NOT DIRECTLY INVOLVED IN THE RESPONSE TO THE SITUATION NOR DOES THE CARRIER HAVE DIRECT KNOWLEDGE OF THE EXACT CIRCUMSTANCES CAUSING THE RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT FROM THE PACKAGE (TANK CAR).  THE CARRIER IS MAKING THIS REPORT SO AS TO COMPLY WITH THE APPLICABLE PROVISIONS OF 49CFR AS THE CARRIER HAS KNOWLEDGE THAT A RELEASE OF PRODUCT DID OCCUR FROM TANK CAR GATX 71782.  ON OCTOBER 28, 2004 THE CARRIER, CSX TRANSPORTATION, WAS CONTACTED BY A THIRD PARTY WHO HAD KNOWLEDGE OF AN ON-GOING INCIDENT IN HUNTINGTON, WV INVOLVING A PUBLIC EVACUATION AND POSSIBLE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THE CARRIER'S REPRESENTATIVE THEN CONTACTED THE 911 DISPATCHER FOR THE CITY OF HUNTINGTON, THE DISPATCHER ADVISED THAT THERE WAS AN INCIDENT ON-GOING AT 4711 PIEDMONT ROAD THAT INVOLVED A RAIL TANK CAR LEAKING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THE 911 DISPATCHER REQUESTED THAT CSXT HALT TRAIN TRAFFIC ON THE TRACKS THAT WERE ADJACENT TO THE PROPERTY IN QUESTION.  CSXT COMPLIED WITH THIS REQUEST.  A CSXT REPRESENTATIVE THEN CONTACTED THE FACILITY (TECHSOL) THAT HAD RECEIVED THE TANK CAR IN QUESTION.  CSXT WAS INFORMED THAT A TANK CAR LOCATED ON THE TECHSOL PROPERTY WAS LEAKING FROM THE "BELLY VALVE." PERSONNEL FROM TECHSOL HAD BEEN IN THE PROCESS OF PREPARING TO OFFLOAD THE CONTENTS OF THE RAIL CAR INTO TRUCKS WHEN THE LEAK OCCURRED.  CSXT CONTINUED TO MONITOR THE SITUATION BUT HAD NO DIRECT INVOLVEMENT IN THE MANAGEMENT, CLEANUP OR INVESTIGATION OF THIS INCIDENT.

column168: AT 10/4/05 AT 0915 PHOENIX FUEL DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HWY 191 MP 43.5.  THE DRIVER DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS LANE AND THE REAR AXLE OF HIS PULL TRAILER LEFT THE TRAVELED PORTION OF THE ROADWAY AND CAUSED THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  THE TRUCK REMAINED UPRIGHT AND THE TRAILER STILL CONNECTED TO THE TRUCK CAME TO REST OFF OF THE ROADWAY IN THE DIRT.  I ARRIVED ON SCENE AT 1045 AND CONTAINED THE SPILLING PRODUCT WITH A DIRT MOUND.  DEPT. OF PUBLIC SAFETY ALLOWED ME TO PUMP RESIDUAL PRODUCT THAT WAS IN THE TRAILER.  AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT THE PULL TRAILER HAD 2953 GALLONS ON BOARD.  WE SALVAGED 1670 GALLONS WHICH LEFT 1283 GALLONS SPILLED.  REMEDIATION STARTED 10/5/05 @ 1100 CT INC. RILLITO ARIZONA WAS IN CHARGE OF THE CLEAN UP.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PROFILED AND DEEMED SOLID WASTE BY AZ DEQ.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PROFILED AND DEEMED SOLID WASTE BY AZDEQ.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS PROFILED AND DEEMED SOLID WASTE BY AZDEQ. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXVACATED AND DISPOSED OF AT BUTTERFIELD REGIONAL LANDFILL.  DURING OUR INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT OUR DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED WHILE DRIVING THE ROADWAY WAS STRAIGHT AND EVEN WITH NO TRAFFIC. WE CONDUCTED SAFETY MEETINGS COVERING DISTRACTED DRIVING AND STOPPED USING CELL PHONES AND C.B. RADIOS WHILE THE VEHICLES ARE IN MOTION.

MECHANIC ARRIVED AT JOB PARKED HIS VEHICLE.  AFTER PARKING VEHICLE MECHANIC WENT UP TO JOB SITE LEAKING TRUCK IN SAME LOCATION.  APPARENTLY, WHILE WORKING IN BUILDING, CONDENSER COIL SCALE REMOVER HAD TIPPED OVER AND BEGAN LEAKING OUT OF VEHICLE.  IN CONCLUSION, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED. MECHANIC WAS NOTIFIED.  HAZMAT ARRIVED TO LOCATION OF INCIDENT AND SPILLAGE WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: AS OF THE DATE OF THIS FILING, THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION INVESTIGATION INTO THIS INCIDENT IS ONGOING.  HOWEVER, INITIAL REPORTS INDICATE THAT RAIL TANK CAR GATX 71782 WAS LOADED BY SLOSS INDUSTRIES IN NORTH BIRMINGHAM, ALABAMA ON 10/14/2004.  IT APPEARS THAT SLOSS DID NOT CHECK THE INTERNAL BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE FOR TOOL TIGHTNESS AS REQUIRED UNDER 49 CFR 173.31 (D) (L) (IV), LEAVING IT IN THE OPEN POSITION.  THE OUTER REDUNDANCY VALVE WAS CLOSED.  THE CAR WAS THEN SHIPPED TO THE TECHSOL CHEMICAL COMPANY SITE IN HUNTINGTON, WEST VIRGINIA.  ON OCTOBER 28, 2004 TECHSOL OPERATORS ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD THE RAIL TANK CAR.  INITIAL REPORTS SUGGEST THAT TECHSOL DID NOT OPERATE THE VALVE ROD AS REQUIRED UNDER 49 CFR 174.67(F) TO ENSURE THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS PROPERLY SEATED BEFORE OPENING THE OUTER, REDUNDANCY VALVE.  ULTIMATELY, APPROXIMATELY 18,500 GALLONS OF COAL TAR LIGHT OIL WAS RELEASED THROUGH THIS BOTTOM VALVE. TECHSOL INITIATED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL RESPONDERS AND AGENCIES HAVE BEEN INVOLVED IN THE RESPONSE FROM THE INCEPTION.  MARATHON ASHLAND PETROLEUM LLC HAS PLAYED A SUPPORT ROLE, RESPONDING TO REQUESTS FOR ASSISTANCE AND AT THE DIRECTION OF AUTHORITIES FROM THE INITIAL INCIDENT REPORTING.  AS NOTED THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION CONTINUES TO INVESTIGATE THE MATTER AT PRESENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN ODOR AND A SLIGHT EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE/STAIN LED TO THE DISCOVERY OF THE DISCREPANCY.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL WHAT APPEARED TO BE A MOTORCYCLE FRAME.  THE FRAME HAD AN ENGINE ATTACHED WHICH WAS APPARENTLY LEAKING GASOLINE AND OIL.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER SURFACE OF THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS OFFERED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER/OFFEROR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JOE DEROUCHE/FAA/SEA.  ON 16:40 (CST) ON 10/04/2004.

INCIDENT OF 10/1/04.  TIME APPROXIMATE 11:00 AM.  MIKE BORSTAD, DRIVER FOR S.B.FUELS OF WYOMING, INC WAS UNLOADING BOTH GAS AND DIESEL FUEL AT THE HIGHWAY DEPT.  IN LARAMIE WY.  WHILE UNLOADING THE DIESEL FUEL THE 6,000 GALLON CON-VAULT OVERFLOWED.  BILL OF LADING SHOWS 2200 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. THIS WAS THE ORDERED AMOUNT BY FRED FROM THE LARAMIE HIGHWAY DEPT.  THE CON-VAULT HAS AN EMERGENCY OVERFLOW VENT IN CASE THE TANK IS OVERFILLED. THE EMERGENCY VENT FAILED TO OPEN.  THE ALARM FOR THE OVERFLOW PROCEDURE WAS ACTIVATED ACCORDING TO FRED WHO WAS IN THE ADJOINING BUILDING, THE ALARM FOR THE INTERSTITIAL AREA BETWEEN THE TANKS DID NOT ACTIVATE.  MY DRIVER FAILED TO HEAR THE ALARM.  WE HAVE DELIVERED TO THIS SITE FOR SEVERAL YEARS AND THE DRIVER HAS BEEN THERE AND DELIVERED TO THIS TANK BEFORE.  OUR BACK UP DRIVER, GLEN GEIHL ARRIVED TO HELP CONTAIN THE PROBLEM ABOUT 12.45 PM.  GLEN REMOVED 196 GALLONS FROM THE TRAILER # 30, THAT WAS DELIVERING THE FUEL. THE ORIGINAL B/L 72407 SHOWS 2200 GALLONS OF "TAX EXEMPT" DIESEL.  I TOOK A PICTURE OF THE METER ON THE 2ND TRANSPORT TO ARRIVE AS IT FINISHED REMOVING DIESEL FROM THE CON-VAULT.  THE METER SHOWS 5877 GALLONS REMOVED FROM THE CON-VAULT.  AFTER I LEFT THE SCENE, THE METER MOVED UP TO 5960 GALLONS.  THE VAULT ONLY HOLDS 6, 000 GALLONS.  IF WE REMOVED 5960 FROM THE CONTAINER, 196 FROM THE DELIVERING TRAILER = 6156. FRED, THE PURCHASING AGENT FOR THE LARAMIE HIGHWAY DEPT. HAS BEEN ORDERING FUEL FOR THAT TANK FOR MANY YEARS.  IT IS NOT LOGICAL THAT HE WOULD ORDER MORE THAN THE TANK WOULD HOLD BY OVER 200 GALLONS.  CONSEQUENTLY, I DON'T BELIEVE THAT MORE THAN 100 GALLONS WERE SPILLED ON THE GROUND.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY THE LARAMIE HIGHWAY BY STACKING SAND AROUND THE AREA. EVERYONE ACTED QUICKLY AND EFFICIENTLY TO STOP THE SPREAD OF THE DIESEL FUEL.  WE CONTACTED THE PROPER AUTHORITIES ASAP.  WE LEFT OUR TRAILER #22 TO CONTAIN THE PUMPED OFF DIESEL UNTIL THE HIGHWAY DEPT. COULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR THE FUEL.  THE VARIANCE BETWEEN THE PICTURE AND THE ACTUAL REMOVED GALLONS IS CHALLENGING.  NORMALLY, WHEN THE METER STOPS THE TANK IS EMPTY.  THE ONLY LOGICAL ANSWER FOR THE INCREASE IN GALLONS IS THAT SOME OF THE FUEL WAS ALREADY IN THE AREA BETWEEN THE CONCRETE AND THE INTERIOR BLADDER.  THE FUEL THAT WAS IN THIS AREA DRAINED OVER TO THE SPOT WERE OUR TRUCK WAS PUMPING THE FUEL OUT AND INTO TRAILER #22.  WHILE GLEN AND I WERE AT THE SCENE, GLEN TESTED THE EMERGENCY VENT.  WE CHECKED WITH EATON METAL OF CASPER, WY WHO REPORTED TO ME THAT THE EMERGENCY VENT WILL OPEN WITH AS 8 OZ OF INTERNAL PRESSURE.  GLEN AND I WERE ON TOP OF THE TANK AND GLEN TRIED TO LIFT THE EMERGENCY RELIEF VENT.  IT WOULD NOT BUDGE.  THE VENT HAD FAILED TO OPEN DUE TO CIRCUMSTANCES OF WHICH I AM NOT AWARE.  BUT AT THE MOMENT HE TRIED TO LIFT IT, THE EMERGENCY VENT WOULD NOT OPEN.  THE PICTURES THAT WERE TAKEN SHOW MINOR SPILLAGE RUNNING NORTH FROM THE CON-VAULT.  THE PICTURES OF THE TANK, SHOW MANY SPLITS IN THE CONCRETE. THE

column168: VEHICLE IDENTIFICATION: 1995 GMC 2-AXLE FLAT BED TRUCK WITH 2-550 GALLON POLYETHYLENE TANKS MOUNTED TO THE TRUCK BED.  DRIVE (THOMAS K. SULLIVAN) WAS EXITING FROM NORTHBOUND INTERSTATE 5 ON THE PORTAL WAY OFF RAMP IN FERNDALE, WASHINGTON.  THE VEHICLE SPEED AT THE OFF RAMP CURVE CAUSED THE CARGO TANK TO SHIFT SLIGHTLY WHICH CAUSED BOTH TANK VALVES TO BREAK.  ABOUT 1,050 GALLONS OF VAPAM HL HERBICIDE WAS SPILLED ON THE OFF RAMP AND THE ADJACENT SOIL.  VAPAM HL IS A MARINE POLLUTANT (METAM-SODIUM). ON 10/13/2004. AT 11:15 AM, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT #738236).  THE WASHINGTON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY WAS ALSO NOTIFIED (REPORT #042560).  THE WASHINGTON STATE PATROL AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL WERE ON SCENE AND SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP.  FOUR NEARBY WORKERS WERE TOLD TO LEAVE THE AREA UNTIL THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE.  THE SPILLED HERBICIDE AND ABSORBENT FROM THE ASPHALT CLEANUP WILL BE DISPOSED OF AT AN APPROVED HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THE EXCAVATED SOIL (ABOUT 70 CUBIC YARDS) WILL BE ANALYZED AND EITHER AGRONOMICALLY APPLIED TO AGRICULTURAL LAND OR DISPOSED OF AS HAZARDOUS WASTE.  DRIVERS DISPOSITION/INCIDENTPREVENTION.  THE DRIVER DID NOT RECEIVE A CITATION AND NO DRUG OR ALCOHOL POST-ACCIDENT TEST WERE DONE.  THE CARGO TANKS MOUNTING WILL BE IMPROVED .  DISCHARGE HOSES WILL NOT BE ATTACHED TO TANKS DURING TRANSPORTATION.  HOSE ENDS AND TANK DISCHARGE VALVES WILL HAVE SAFETY CAPS IN PLACE AT ALL TIMES, EXCEPT DURING UNLOADING.

column168: AT 10:55 AM ON OCTOBER 14, 2004, A SMALL SPILL OF PCB OIL (ORIGINALLY ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN ONE PINT, OR ABOUT ONE POUND FROM VISUAL OBSERVATIONS), WAS DISCOVERED IN A VAN TRAILER THAT WAS TRANSPORTING ELECTRICAL TRANSFORMERS TO THE CWM-LCH FACILITY FOR TRANSSHIPMENT TO AN APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CWM-LCH FACILITY CONTAINER MANAGEMENT UNIT, SITE PERSONNEL OPENED THE VAN TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY DISCOVERED THE LEAK; SEE THE ATTACHED PHOTOGRAPH.  IT APPEARED THAT ONE TRANSFORMER LEAKED SOME PCB OIL (CAS NO. 1336-36-3, DOT ID NO. UN2315, HAZARD CLASS 9) AND A SECOND TRANSFORMER CAME IN CONTACT WITH THIS LEAKED PCB OIL.  NO PCB'S LEAKED FROM OR THROUGH THE STEEL FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  CWM-LCH PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY OVER PACKED THE TWO TRANSFORMERS WHICH HAD PCB'S ON THEIR OUTSIDE CASINGS; THE SIX OTHER TRANSFORMERS IN THE LOAD WERE ALSO OVER PACKED AS A PRECAUTION.  ALSO, IN THE AFTERNOON OF OCTOBER 14, 2004, THE AREA OF THE SPILL IN THE VAN WAS CORDONED OFF TO PREVENT TRACKING OF THE PCB'S FROM THE VAN TRAILER AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND LATER REMOVED.  BY NOON ON OCTOBER 15, 2004, THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED BY TRIPLE RINSING THE SPILL AREA WITH DIESEL FUEL IN ACCORDANCE WITH 40 CFR 761; CONFIRMATION OF DECONTAMINATION USING PROCEDURES CONTAINED IN 40 CFR 761 IS UNDERWAY WITH LABORATORY TESTS OF SWABS BEING CONDUCTED.  THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) FOR PCB'S IS ONE POUND AND THE ORIGINAL ESTIMATE OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABOUT ONE POUND.  TO PROVIDE A CLOSER ESTIMATE OF WHAT VOLUME (AND WEIGHT) ACTUALLY SPILLED, A TEST WAS DONE TO OCTOBER 20, 2004.  WATER WAS SPILLED ON THE SAME SURFACE UNTIL IT VISUALLY APPROXIMATED THE EXTENT OF THE "FOOTPRINT" OF THE ORIGINAL SPILL.  FROM OBSERVATIONS OF THIS TEST, IT IS NOW CONCLUDED THAT ONLY ABOUT ONE-QUARTER OF A PINT, OR ABOUT ONE-THIRD OF A POUND OF PCB'S ACTUALLY SPILLED IN THE VAN TRAILER.  THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE SPILL IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  PRELIMINARY, IT APPEARS THAT THESE TRANSFORMERS SHOULD HAVE BEEN PACKAGED WITHIN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT DUE TO THEIR AGE AND THE MANNER IN WHICH THEY WERE LOADED ON THE VAN.  THE GENERATOR OF THE WASTES IS: THE TERMCO CO 1249 JOEL BLANCHARD ST. PARKS, LA 70582 THE FIRST TRANSPORTER OF THE WASTE WAS: CEI 1129A FLORIDA BLVD. WALKER, LA 70785  THE SECOND TRANSPORTER OF THE WASTE WAS: CWM TRANSPORTATION, INC. 7123 JOHN BRANNON ROAD SULPHUR, LA 70665  FROM THE ATTACHED "NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST NO. WM-015054, CEI PICKED UP THE LOAD ON OCTOBER 13, 2004 AND DELIVERED IT TO THE CWM 10-DAY STORAGE FACILITY LOCATED AT THE CWM FACILITY.  CWM TRANSPORTATION THEN DELIVERED THE LOAD TO THE CONTAINER MANAGEMENT UNIT ON OCTOBER 14, 2004.  PRESENTLY, THE TRANSFORMERS ARE OVER PACKED AND STORED IN THE PERMITTED CONTAINER MANAGEMENT UNIT, AWAITING TRANSPORT OFF-SITE TO AN APPROVED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  ALL RESIDUALS FROM CLEANUP OF THE SPILL, ESTIMATED TO BE ABOUT ONE 55-GALLON DRUM IN VOLUME, WILL BE SHIPPED OFF-SITE FOR DISPOSAL

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1830 HOURS, 10-21-04, AN APRIA HEALTHCARE TRUCK, 2001 ISUZU FRR, VAN WITH A CARGO TANK CONTAINING LIQUID OXYGEN, WAS W/B ON I 580, APPROXIMATELY 1/10 MILE EAST OF MILE POST 580 ALA 13-22.  THE VEHICLE WAS DRIVEN BY APRIA HEALTHCARE EMPLOYEE CHRIS L FRAUENDORFER FROM THE APRIA HEALTHCARE, LIVERMORE, CA OFFICE.  FRAUENDORFER WAS TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 55 MPH WHEN HE LOOKED DOWN TO PICK UP AN UNKNOWN OBJECT.  IN DOING SO HE ALLOWED THE VEHICLE TO DRIFT ONTO THE RIGHT SHOULDER.  HE THEN LOOKED UP AND OBSERVED A 1998 FORD CONTOUR PARKED ALONG THE RIGHT SHOULDER. HE SWERVED TO THE LEFT IN AN ATTEMPT TO AVOID THE PARKED VEHICLE.  HE WAS UNABLE TO AVOID A COLLISION WITH THE REAR OF THE PARKED VEHICLE.  BOTH VEHICLES OVERTURNED AND CAME TO REST DOWN AN EMBANKMENT.  THE LIVERMORE-PLEASANTON FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND TREATED FRAUENDORFER FOR MINOR INJURIES.  HE WAS TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR EXAMINATION AND LATER RELEASED WITH MINOR INJURIES. THERE WERE NO PASSENGERS IN THE FORD CONTOUR.  FIRE PERSONNEL FOUND A WHITE VAPOR CLOUD COMING FROM THE APRIA HEALTHCARE VEHICLE AND CYLINDERS, MEDICAL COMPRESSED OXYGEN, LYING ON THE GROUND.  UPON MAKING ENTRANCE TO THE VEHICLE CARGO AREA THEY FOUND THAT THE LIQUID OXYGEN THAT WAS LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANK WAS DISSIPATING IN A NON-HAZARDOUS AREA.  THE MSDS WAS LOCATED IN THE VEHICLE.  A SECONDARY INSPECTION FOUND NO OTHER PRIMARY HAZARDS.  THE EXAMINATION CONDUCTED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL FAILED TO FIND A LEAK IN THE CARGO TANK.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE LOSS OF LIQUID OXYGEN WAS A RESULT OF THE CARGO TANK BEING INVERTED AND LIQUID ESCAPING THROUGH THE VENTING SYSTEM.  THE LIQUID OXYGEN HAD FINISHED VENTING OFF BEFORE CAL TRANS ARRIVED ON THE SCENE FOR ACCIDENT RELATED CLEAN UP.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD DECLARED THAT THERE WAS NO FIRE HAZARD AND DEPARTED.  THE CYLINDERS (OXYGEN, COMPRESSED) WERE RECOVERED BY APRIA HEALTHCARE PERSONNEL WHO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE TRUCK WAS TRANSPORTED TO A STORAGE YARD WHERE THE CARGO TANK WAS REMOVED FOR SHIPMENT TO US TANK FOR INSPECTION AND REFURBISHMENT.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, RELEASE.  THE ONLY INJURIES WERE THE MINOR INJURIES SUSTAINED BY FRAUENDORFER.

column168: ON OCTOBER 20, 2004, PERSONNEL IN THE CSX RAILYARD IN TALLAHASSEE, FL DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM CITX 33431, A LOADED TANK CAR OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT 05:45 ON OCTOBER 20, 2004, THE COLTON PHARMACY RECEIVED A CALL FROM CUSTOMER SERVICE ASSISTANT, JERRY CASEL.  JERRY INFORMED US THAT WHILE DRIVING IN HEAVY RAIN CONDITIONS HIS VEHICLE HIT A FLOODED AREA OF THE ROADWAY AND WAS JUST INVOLVED IN A ROLL OVER VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  HE STATED THAT AMMO CANS CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD BEEN EJECTED FROM THE VEHICLE AND CAME TO REST OVER PORTIONS OF THE 10 FREEWAY WESTBOUND.  ONE CAN IN PARTICULAR HAD BEEN CRUSHED AND OPENED BY A 18 WHEEL SEMI TRACTOR TRAILER RIG AND ITS CONTENTS WAS BEING SPEWED AND RUN OVER BY OTHER VEHICLES IN OTHER TRAFFIC LANES.  JERRY MANAGED TO SECURE AS MANY CANS AS POSSIBLE TO PREVENT OTHERS FROM BEING DAMAGED.  PARAMEDICS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND JERRY INFORMED THEM OF WHAT HAD JUST OCCURRED.  PARAMEDICS SPOKE WITH ROBERT BELLIZZI, RSO AT THE COLTON LAB VIA 2-WAY RADIO.  ROBERT INFORMED THE PARAMEDICS THAT HE WAS THE RSO OF THE FACILITY WHERE THE SHIPMENT HAD ORIGINATED.  HE ADVISED THEM THAT JERRY WAS INDEED CARRYING DIAGNOSTIC RADIOPHARMACEUTICALS CONTAINING TC99M AND T1-201.  SAN BERNARDINO'S LOCAL HAZ-MAT WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL.  ROBERT IMMEDIATELY REPORTED THE FACTS OF THE INCIDENT TO CARDINAL HEALTH'S QUALITY AND REGULATORY PERSONNEL AND THE COLTON PHARMACY MANAGER. ROBERT INFORMED Q&R THAT HE WAS PREPARING TO GO TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT, WHICH WAS ABOUT 3 MILES FROM THE PHARMACY.  ROBERT THEN CALLED AZIZ MAKHANI, RPH TO COVER THE SHIFT SO THAT HE COULD LEAVE THE FACILITY TO SURVEY THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  AZIZ ARRIVED AT THE PHARMACY AT 06:30. ROBERT LEFT THE PHARMACY AT 06:35 WITH A SURVEY METER, GLOVES, FORCEPS, EMPTY PIGS, AND SPARE AMMO CAN.  SHIPPING PAPERS IDENTIFYING THE CONTENTS OF WHAT JERRY HAD BEEN CARRYING WERE ALSO COPIED AND TAKEN TO THE SCENE. HE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 06:50.  WHEN HE OBSERVED IN THE POURING RAIN WAS A CARDINAL HEALTH DELIVERY TRUCK OVERTURNED ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE WESTBOUND SIDE OF THE 10 FREEWAY WITH AMMO CANS, PIGS, AND VARIOUS OTHER VEHICLE DEBRIS VISIBLE ON THE HIGHWAY.  TWO OF THE 4 TRAFFIC LANES HAS BEEN CLOSED TO TRAFFIC.  ROBERT WAS GREETED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL UNIT, FIRE DEPT, AND THE CHP.  THEY ASKED SEVERAL QUESTIONS ABOUT WHAT WAS ON THE TRUCK, HOW MANY DOSES AND WHAT ACTUALLY WAS BEING CARRIED.  ROBERT EXPLAINED THE NATURE OF CARDINALS HEALTH'S NUCLEAR PHARMACY BUSINESS AND ADVISED THEM THAT IF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD INDEED SPILLED ONTO THE ROADWAY, IT WAS BEING WASHED AWAY AND DILUTED BECAUSE OF THE HEAVY DOWNPOURS WE WERE EXPERIENCING.  HE EXPLAINED WHAT FIRST NEEDED TO BE DONE WAS TO ACCOUNT FOR ALL AMMO CANS AND DOSES.  AT 07:20 MIKE MATUS, PHARMACY MANAGER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  JERRY LEFT THE COLTON PHARMACY AT 05:00 WITH SIX AMMO CANS CONTAINING RADIOACTIVE DOSES.  PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT, JERRY MANAGED TO DELIVER TO THREE HOSPITALS WITH LIMITED QUANTITY IN RETURNS TOTALING TWO AMMO CANS.  THE REMAINING THREE "OUTGOING" AMMO CANS CONTAINING RAM WAS TO BE DELIVERE

column168: E.M.I. JOB #20104, TRACTOR TRAILER UNIT WAS EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE HIGHWAY 20/59 NEAR LIVINGSTON, ALABAMA.  THE UNIT LEFT THE ROAD AND WENT THROUGH A GUARDRAIL.  THE UNIT CAME TO REAR UP-RIGHT ON THE TRIBUTARY CREEK.  THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND ONE 55-GALLON DRUM OF ACRYLIC ACID WAS PUNCTURED. APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE DRUM. MGR. LERCH RESPONDED, AND CONTACTED THE RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION.  UPON ARRIVAL, MGR. LERCH NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON PER HOUR WITH NO POOLING OF PRODUCT.  MGR. LERCH IMMEDIATELY PLACED A BUCKET TO CONTAIN THE LEAK, AND CLOSED PARTIALLY OPEN BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AFTER TEMPORARILY STOPPING THE LEAK, MGR. LERCH HAD THE CAR SET-OUT INTO AN ISOLATION TRACK FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  UPON CLOSER INSPECTION, MGR. LERCH NOTED THE TWO INCH BOTTOM OUTLET CAP PLUG TO BE GALLED WHICH PREVENTED PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE CAR.  ADDITIONALLY, THE BOTTOM OUTLET BALL VALVE WAS NOTED TO BE PARTIALLY OPEN CAUSING PRODUCT LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP ASSEMBLY.  AFTER DETERMINING CAUSE OF THE RELEASE, MGR. LERCH CONTACTED BRIAN SOSSAMAN, EMERGENCY RESPONSE COORDINATOR FOR LYONDELL/EQUISTAR, AND ADVISED HIM THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE PERSONNEL RESPOND AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  ON ARRIVAL, OF LYONDELL PERSONNEL, THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP ASSEMBLY WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS NOR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, NOR ANY REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.  ADDITIONALLY, THERE WAS NO CLEAN-UP REQUIRED AS PRODUCT EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.

column168: TOBY TREVETT, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, REPORTED AN EMPLOYEE WAS EXPOSED TO A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN THE AVONDALE, LA RAIL YARD.  DENNIS FALCON, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, WAS ENROUTE TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL WITH THE EMPLOYEE.  AT 04:11 PM, THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED DOCTOR GOAD, CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH, WAS CONFERRED WITH THE EMPLOYEE WHO HAD BEEN TAKEN TO PELICAN CLINIC.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED WITH NO COMPLICATIONS.  ROBINSON ALSO RELATED THAT EAGLE CONST AND ENV SERVICES WHO RESPONDING WITH HAZMAT TECHNICIANS TO ASSIST SAHM TREVETT. IN ADDITION, DOW CHEMICAL (UNION CARBIDE) AT TAFT SENT THREE HAZMAT TECHNICIANS TO ASSIST AS WELL. OPERATIONS IN THE NORTH YARD WERE SHUT DOWN. SAHM TREVETT, ADVISED REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE LOUISIAN STATE POLICE, DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, AND EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE ON SCENE FOR AIR MONITORING. THE RAILCAR WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS FOUND THE RAILCAR WAS OVERFILLED. MR. TREVETT STATED ALL EIGHT BOLTS ON THE MAN WAY COVER PLATED WERE ALSO LOOSE. THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAKAGE STOPPED. AFTER SECUREMENT, THE RAILCAR WAS PLACED ON AN EXPEDITED MOVE. DOW (UNION CARBIDE) TO HANDLE THE LOAD REDUCTION AS SOON AS POSSIBLE.

STEVE DULAND, TERMINAL MANAGER, REPORTED A CONTAINER WAS LEAKING AN UNKNOWN AMOUNT OF PRODUCT AT THE CANAL YARD IN CHICAGO, IL.  STEVE ADVISED CONTAINER UPTU 660028 WAS LOCATED NEAR THE MAIN OFFICE.  MARK MADAY, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE CONTAINER AND POOLED ON THE PAVEMENT.  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE CONTAINER TO COLLECT ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT.  THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  AT 11:23 PM, MADAY REPORTED PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSFERRED INTO CONTAINER UPTU 660150.  SCT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO HANDLE REMEDIATION.

column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED IM TANK NRSU 182100, LOCATED IN THE ICTF INTERMODAL FACILITY, MILE POST 498.3, LONG BEACH, CA WAS LEAKING AND PRODUCING A GAS ODOR.  OFFICER SANCHEZ FURTHER STATED A SMALL PUDDLE, APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON, HAD LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND EN ROUTE.  AT 11:37 AM, MANAGER COOPER REPORTED HE FOUND NO SIGN OF ANY LIQUID LEAK OTHER THAN SOME CONDENSATION AT THE LOWER RIGHT HAND REAR CORNER FRAME WHERE THE LOCKING PIN FROM THE CHASSIS ATTACHES.  MR. COOPER STATED THE CONTAINER HAD A TRACE ODOR OF THE ETHYL MERCAPTIAN COMING FROM THE LOWER BELLY OF THE TANK NEAR WHERE THE DRIP TUBES EXTEND OUT.  MANAGER COOPER REQUESTED STATE AND LOCAL AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS, ALONG WITH CHEMTREC FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION.  AT 02:37 PM, MANAGER COOPER REPORTED THE IM TANK WAS VENTING FROM ONE OF THE FOUR VALVES AT THE TOP OF THE TANK, BUT WAS UNABLE TO ISOLATE WHICH VALVE WAS THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE TANK WAS A RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED, RETURNING TO NATURAL GAS ODORIZING, BAYTOWN TEXAS.  STEVE HANNAH FROM NATURAL GAS ODORIZING ADVISED THE TANK BELONGS TO TAIWAN SODA AROMATIC, TAIWAN, A CUSTOMER HE PROVIDES WITH THE PRODUCT.  THE LIQUID LINE HAD AN OVERSIZED GASKET ON THE FLANGE, WHICH INDICATED THE VALVE HAD BEEN WORKED ON BY THE CUSTOMER.  MR. HANNAH CONFIRMED HE DID NOT USE THAT TYPE OF GASKET WHEN HE HAD TO REPAIR FLANGE LEAKS.  DEVELOPED ALL FOUR OF THE FLANGE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE WERE LOOSE, AND COULD BE TURNED ALMOST A FULL TURN TO WRENCH TIGHTEN.  THE THREE REMAINING VALVE FLANGES WERE ALSO TIGHTENED A MINIMUM OF 3/4 OF A TURN FOR EACH OF THE BOLTS.  THE FOLLOW UP INSPECTION FOUND THE TOP VALVE COMPARTMENT VOID OF ANY ODORS AFTER ALL THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED.  THE VAPOR RELEASE APPEARED TO BE FROM THE LOOSE LIQUID LINE FLANGE WITH THE OVERSIZED GASKET, HOWEVER, IT COULD NOT DETERMINED CONCLUSIVELY.  THE TANK WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER UNLOADING GASOLINE AT ABOVE GROUND BULK PLANT IN POLSON, MT.  WHILE IN PROCESS OF UNLOADING, DRIVER UNLOADED GASOLINE INTO THE WRONG TANK AND OVERFILLED THE TANK.  PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE TOP OF CUSTOMERS TANK AND SPILLED INTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA.  APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF UL GASOLINE SPILLED AND WAS CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY THE SAME DAY.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO MONTANA DES.  INCIDENT #04102102 AND NRC, INCIDENT #739062.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE BOX WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED AND LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS RECOUPED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM WITH A CHEMICAL LINER, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.  REMAINING SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR TRUCK WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DELIVERING FUEL TO A STATION.  DRIVER HAD PULLED INTO THE STATION AND SPOTTED HIS UNIT IN THE DELIVERY POSITION. DRIVER HAD PLACED WARNING CONES TO CREATE A SAFE AREA FOR DELIVERY.  A CAR WAS MARKED AT THE PUMPS WITH ANOTHER CAR PARKED AT THE SAME PUMPS IN FRONT OF HIM.  OUR DRIVER STATES THERE WAS SOME TYPE OF ALTERCATION ACROSS THE STREET INVOLVING A WOMAN YELLING.  THE DRIVER OF THE 2ND CAR PARKED AT THE PUMPS AND A PASSENGER DECIDED THEY WERE GOING TO HELP HER AND JUMPED BACK INTO THEIR CAR AND BACKED OUT OF THE PUMP AREA AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED AND RAN OVER OUR CONES, HOSE AND FITTING.  AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION THE FITTING BEGAN TO LEAK FUEL.  OUR DRIVER WAS STANDING RIGHT BY THE SHUTOFF VALVES AND STOPPED THE FLOW OF FUEL RIGHT AWAY, LIMITING THE SPILL TO THE FUEL THAT WAS IN THE HOSE.  AFTER STOPPING THE FLOW OUR DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DAM THE FLOW WITH OUR SPILL KITS.  ABOUT 36 GALLONS OF FUEL SPILLED AND A SMALL PORTION WAS ABLE TO GET TO THE STORM DRAIN BEFORE THE DRIVER COULD STOP IT.  OUR DISPATCH AS WELL AS PD AND FD WERE NOTIFIED FOR RESPONSE.  FD HAZMAT REFUSED TO RESPOND BECAUSE OF THE SPILL SIZE.  COAST GUARD, OES, FISH & GAME AND COUNTY HEALTH WERE NOTIFIED.  THE ONLY ACTION REQUESTED BY ANYONE CONTACTED WAS PUMPING OUT THE STORM DRAIN BY COUNTY HEALTH AS A PRECAUTION.  THIS WAS DONE AND CLEARED BY THEM.  THE AMOUNT OF LIQUID PUMPED FROM THE STORM DRAIN INCLUDED WATER USED BY THE FD TO WASH DOWN THE AREA AFTER CLEANUP.  THE MANIFEST LISTS 50 GALLONS OF OILY WATER NON RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE LIQUID.  THE STORM BOX IS ABOUT 3 X 2 BEFORE PUMPING THERE WAS ABOUT 1/4 OF THE SURFACE AREA THAT HAD A FILM ON IT.  THAT FILM HAD NO COLOR TO IT AND NO ODOR OF FUEL.

column168: DONNED PPE.  REFERRED TO DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS.  DISPOSED OF CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD AND ENTIRE CONTENTS THROUGH DMP.

column168: DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO WRONG ADDRESS CAUSING OIL TO SPILL IN BASEMENT. PROFESSIONAL REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AND OIL SPILL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED, CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF.

column168: INBOUND SUPERVISOR SAM ENGLISH LOADED PRO 341185885 ONTO TRAILER 926636 ON 10/6/04.  MR. ENGLISH FAILED TO BLOCK THE 2,235 LB TOTE IN THE TRAILER. WHEN MR. EDDIE MEADOWS, CITY DRIVER, ARRIVED AT HOME OIL AND GAS TO DELIVER THIS TOTE, IT WAS FOUND THAT A HOPPER LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER HAD SHIFTED AND STRUCK THE TOTE CREATING A GASH IN THE TOTE.  THE SPILLAGE OCCURRED IN THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CUSTOMERS ASPHALT LOT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE AND CALLED THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE DELIVERY RECEIPT.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE SHIPPER TO CONTAIN THE SPILL WITH OIL DRY TYPE ABSORBENT.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND THEY RESPONDED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SURROUNDED THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT BOOMS AND OIL DRY ABSORBENT.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALSO CALLED THE VDOT AND THEY RESPONDED WITH ABOUT A TON OF GRAVEL, AND THIS WAS SPREAD OUT OVER THE SPILL AREA.  THE ABSORBENT AND BOOMS WERE CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO STEEL RECOVERY DRUMS.  MR. SAM ENGLISH HAS BEEN ISSUED A WRITTEN CORRECTIVE ACTION FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW HAZMAT PROCEDURES AND PROPER WORK INSTRUCTIONS.

DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO WRONG PROPERTY CAUSING OIL TO SPILL INTO BASEMENT. DRIVER CALLED SERVICE DEPARTMENT TO LAY DOWN SORBENT DUST.  THE REST OF PROPERTY MITIGATION IS BEING HANDLED BY MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL.

column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON 10/14/2004 SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ONTO A TRAILER LOADED TO USL-SALINAS IN DOOR 5, WHEN DRIVER REYES RAMIREZ/UIV-IRVINE CRUSHED A BOX OF PAINT MATERIALS UPON LOADING.  HE WAS ENTERING THE TRAILER AND DID NOT MOVE THE BOX OF PAINT AND STRUCK IT WITH THE FORKLIFT.  I WAS THE SUPERVISOR THAT INVESTIGATED THE SPILL AND SPOKE WITH MR. RAMIREZ, WHICH AGREED THAT HE STRUCK THE BOX.  THERE WERE TWO BOXES IN THE SHIPMENT ONE BOX WAS DAMAGED TWO OF THE PAILS WERE CRUSHED AND LEAKED THE OTHER TWO WERE CONTAMINATED BY THE PAINT LACQUER.

WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED A VAPOR CLOUD WAS NOTICED INSIDE THE TRAILER. FREIGHT (CYLINDERS) WERE LAYING FLAT ONE OF THE CYLINDERS HAD FALLEN OFF THE PALLET DO TO NOT BE PROPERLY SECURED AND THE VALVE WAS LEAKING OUT.  ED BOE AND MIKE SORRENSON SAFETY SUPERVISORS FOR CONWAY WESTERN EXPRESS WERE NOTIFIED FOR PROPER INSTRUCTIONS.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AFTER INSTRUCTIONS WERE GIVEN.  TRAILER WAS STAGED OUT BEHIND OUR SHOP AWAY FROM THE SERVICE CENTER HAZ-MAR RESPONSE TEAM CAME OUT AND CLEANED UP THE GAS LEAK.
